comments.body:
@jfath have you tried to configure the machine with user-mode networking: `podman machine init --user-mode-networking`?

Another thing you can try is to manually run win-sshproxy (the utility Podman uses to create the named pipe). You can have a look at the output of `podman machine start --log-level=debug` to see how `win-sshproxy` is executed.

Let me know how it goes.

In my environment the application event log is not accessible to non-admin users.  Looking at the win-sshproxy source, I see that when logging is setup, if logrus fails in eventlog.Open(".NET Runtime") and that error is not RPC_S_SERVER_UNAVAILABLE, then it does os.Exit(1).  That's exactly what I'm seeing - no console output of error messages and (of course) nothing in the event log.

I wonder if it would be possible fallback to console output?  I should probably do an issue report in gvisor-tap-vsock.

@l0rd  Thanks again for your help.
